    ## Design tokens in Apex Kit for Web components

    The property-value pairs that represent color, typography, size,
    spacing, and other attributes are managed in YAML. During the build
    process, <span class="underline">SCSS variables and maps</span> are
    generated, as is a JSON file used as data in JavaScript and other
    applications.

    ```scss
    @mixin eds-heading-level-3() {
        color: $eds-text-color-primary;
        font-family: $eds-font-family-sans
        font-size: $eds-font-size-heading-level-3;
        font-weight: $eds-font-weight-bold;
        line-height: $eds-font-line-height-heading;
    }
    ```

    The <em>***Level*** 3 Heading</em> mixin relies on
    color, family, size, weight, and line-height attributes.

    ```scss
        $eds-font-line-height-normal: 1.5;
        $eds-font-line-height-heading: 1.25;
    ```

    Common styling attributes, like line-height, are “spec-ed” with a
    limited range of values to promote visual alignment across pages. They
    are named in descriptive terms to communicate clear design intent.


    ## Using design tokens

    When creating new components using Providence visual
    style, When applying Providence visual style, use tokens for as
    many style attributes as possible. If a visual standard must be tweaked,
    the markup and CSS will remain untouched.

    ### Styling with tokens

    “Syntax callout” component with caption

    ```scss
    .tbd-component-container {
    background-color: $eds-color-background-light-gray;
    border-radius: $eds-radius-M;
    padding: $eds-space-inset-squish-two-x;
    }
    ```

    **Consider** using existing design tokens that are managed indirectly in
    SCSS.

    ### Styling without tokens

    ```scss
    .tbd-component-container {
        background-color:\#F2F2F2;
        border-radius: 0.1875rem;
        padding: 1rem 2rem;
    }
    ```
    **­Avoid** using values that are managed directly in CSS.


    ## Contributing new tokens

    Please follow the **<em>standard contribution
    process</em>** for contributing new tokens or proposing changes to
    existing ones.


